Why Juvenal should have chosen verse as the appropriate vehicle of his thoughts may seem at first a little difficult to explain. M. N isard has expressed an opinion that Juvenal's real position in literature is that of a declaimer3 and that his style represents a constant struggle between the energetic conciseness natural to himself and the diffuseness taught in the schools of rhetoric. We have seen from the scanty records of Juvenal’s life that he declaimed in the schools till he was nearly of middle age3 and no one can doubt that his style everywhere recals the orator. The lavish use of illustration, the frequent introduction of dialogue, the fervid straightforwardness of words, are all congenial to the best practice of the orator. N evertheless the very tenus of M. Nisard's criticism suggest a doubt as to its thoroughness. We have in Juvenal a consummate master of style, who has been trained for twenty years as a rhetorician, and who wields a language that was at least as perfect for prose as for verse. All at once this man deliberately chooses verse as the vehicle of his thoughts, and creates unmistakeable master-pieces, transcending his own rude models, Lucilius Varro, ay and even Horace, and influencing modern litera- ture in its best period. Can anyone seriously think that Juvenal would have left his mark in this way, if he had written prose declamations?
